n =0Aby two of its co-founders and it is very tempting to think of them as =
the Two =0ASigmas. They do not embody teamwork:=0A=0AThe billionaire founde=
rs of Two Sigma Investments =E2=80=94 John Overdeck and David =0ASiegel =E2=
=80=94 are stepping down from day-to-day management after feuding for years=
 =0Aand handing control to two new co-chief executive officers.=0A=0AThey w=
ill remain co-chairmen and advise the $60 billion firm on quant =0Ainvestin=
g and technology, and their equity stakes will remain unchanged, =0Aaccordi=
ng to a letter to investors Wednesday that was seen by Bloomberg. Chief =0A=
Business Officer Carter Lyons, a 13-year-veteran of the firm, and former La=
zard =0Ageneral counsel Scott Hoffman will take over as co-CEOs on Sept. 30=
.=0A=0AThe relationship between Overdeck and Siegel had become so strained=
 that Two =0ASigma identified the rift as a material risk in a March 2023 r=
egulatory filing =0A=E2=80=94 an unusual move for any hedge fund, let alone=
 one as secretive as Two Sigma. =0AThe firm=E2=80=99s biggest management ov=
erhaul in its 23-year history is aimed at =0Afostering improved collaborati=
on among its most senior leaders.=0A=0AHedge fund firms are a bit like tech=
 startups in that, when you start out, the =0Afounder/CEO mostly needs tech=
nical and fundraising skills, but when you mature =0Ainto a giant firm what=
 you need are administrative and diplomatic skills. Some =0Afounder/CEOs ma=
ture seamlessly from one version to another, but some don=E2=80=99t.=0A=0A=
=0AWho controls a central bank=3F=0A=0ABlockchain solves this =0A<https://w=
ww.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2024-08-28/libya-s-central-bank-coup-turns-t=
o-farce-with-plea-for-passwords=3Fcmpid=3DBBD082824_MONEYSTUFF&utm_medium=
=3Demail&utm_source=3Dnewsletter&utm_term=3D240828&utm_campaign=3Dmoneystuf=
f>=0A:=0A=0AThe plot to wrest control of Libya=E2=80=99s central bank from =
its embattled governor =0Ahad everything from an executive order to policem=
en surrounding the building. =0AWhat it lacked was one crucial element: the=
 passwords needed to actually take =0Aover operations.=0A=0AAs the new lead=
ership backed by one of the OPEC nation=E2=80=99s two rival governments =0A=
settles into the bank=E2=80=99s waterfront headquarters in the capital, Tri=
poli, any =0Asense of victory is fleeting. Not only has the competing admin=
istration in =0ALibya=E2=80=99s east shut down oil production in response, =
but the regulator=E2=80=99s new =0Astaff are struggling to get payments flo=
wing again.=0A=0A=E2=80=9CI will tell you one thing: give the people the pa=
sswords,=E2=80=9D Abdel-Fattah =0AGhaffar, the new interim deputy governor,=
 said Tuesday in a televised briefing =0Ameant to reassure the public the b=
ank was in safe hands. The appeal to his =0Aousted predecessor, Sadiq Al-Ka=
bir =E2=80=94 whereabouts currently unknown =E2=80=94 appeared =0Ato fall o=
n deaf ears.=0A=0AThe snafu is the latest twist in a potentially dangerous =
showdown between =0ALibya=E2=80=99s dueling eastern and western governments=
 over an institution whose =0Acontrol of billions of dollars of oil revenue=
 make it a prize asset.=0A=0AI=E2=80=99m kidding; obviously blockchain does=
n=E2=80=99t solve this. [7]  <> But we talk =0A<https://www.bloomberg.com/o=
