le=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"> <li s=
tyle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Left would short a stock and then publish a ne=
gative report about the stock. When he published the report, the stock woul=
d usually go down. Then he would pretty=C2=A0quickly cover his short (buy b=
ack most or all of the stock he had shorted), making a quick profit from th=
e drop caused by his report.</li> <li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">His rep=
ort was quite clear that he had=C2=A0<em>shorted=C2=A0</em>the stock, but h=
e didn=E2=80=99t tell people publicly when he=C2=A0<em>covered=C2=A0</em>hi=
s short by buying back the stock, and in fact he sometimes would go on Twit=
ter or television to say that he was still short when he wasn=E2=80=99t.</l=
i></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">My basic analysis was:</p><ul style=3D"=
list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"> <li style=3D"m=
argin-bottom: 5px;">Point 1 above is=C2=A0<em>obviously fine=C2=A0</em>=E2=
=80=94=C2=A0you are allowed to do that and it is not fraud =E2=80=94=C2=A0e=
ven though it rubs people the wrong way. The only way for Left=E2=80=99s re=
ports to consistently move stocks, for years, was if the reports were=C2=A0=
<em>often right</em>, and in fact many of his reports were right. It didn=
=E2=80=99t matter if he covered his shorts quickly after his reports were p=
ublished: Left would take the quick profit so he could move on to another s=
hort, but the only reason the quick profit was available was that other inv=
estors believed his claims. There was a division of labor, in which Left id=
entified the short opportunities and took a commission, while other investo=
rs committed capital to longer-term short bets based on his analysis.</li> =
<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Point 2 has some bad facts, sure. I don=
=E2=80=99t think Left was required to disclose the minute he covered his sh=
orts, but on the other hand you shouldn=E2=80=99t go around <em>actively ly=
ing</em> about your positions.</li> <li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">It se=
ems relevant to=C2=A0<em>me</em>, though not to the SEC, whether Left=E2=80=
=99s actual reports were mostly honest, diligent and correct, or mostly non=
sense that he made up to manipulate the stocks. As far as I can tell, the a=
nswer was mostly the former.</li></ul><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">What are=
 the takeaways for other activist short sellers=3F (Not legal advice!) The =
most obvious takeaway is: Don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>lie=C2=A0</em>about your p=
ositions; if you short a stock, publish a report, cover your short and=C2=
=A0<em>then=C2=A0</em>get asked on television =E2=80=9Chave you bought back=
 any stock,=E2=80=9D you should probably say things like =E2=80=9Cno commen=
t=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cyes=E2=80=9D or =E2=80=9Cwe stand by our report and =
think that this stock will go down in the long term, but our business model=
 involves limiting risk and taking advantage of the short-term impact of ou=
r report, so yes we have bought back stock.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">But maybe the broader takeaway is that you have to be more =
careful about=C2=A0the overall business model. In particular, the SEC seems=
 to think that there is something=C2=A0<em>inherently deceptive=C2=A0</em>a=
bout activist short sellers=C2=A0covering their=C2=A0shorts quickly after=
=C2=A0publishing their reports.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The SEC is =
wrong about that, but you can always add more disclosure. If you publish a =
short report saying =E2=80=9Cwe are short XYZ, we think it=C2=A0will go to =
zero,=C2=A0but if the stock goes down after we publish this report we are g=
oing to cover our short quickly,=E2=80=9D then the SEC can=E2=80=99t really=
 say you were being deceptive, can it=3F=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
